webpackJsonp([0xfef002065b61],{508:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{wordpressWpLessons:{id:"9783d2db-b816-584b-b149-6d41aa14f732",wordpress_id:6685,title:"Activity: Practicing CSS Part 1",slug:"activity-practicing-css-part-1",content:'<h2> Objectives and Overview</h2>\n<p>This lesson provides hands-on activities for you to practice CSS in <a href="http://thimble.mozilla.org">Thimble</a>. Make sure that you&#8217;ve completed the previous HTML lessons and activities before starting this activity, as you&#8217;ll need to be familiar with HTML basics.</p>\n<h3>Lesson Objectives:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Practice your CSS skills by remixing starter Thimble projects</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<h2 class="learn-activity">Activity: Remixing Thimble Projects</h2>\n<p>Thimble has two introductory CSS activities that are fun and illustrate how CSS works. The first is the <em>Build-a-Burger</em> activity and the second is a <em>CSS Blocks</em> activity. These are some fun, quick projects that you can remix. Let&#8217;s get started!</p>\n<h3>HTML and CSS Burger</h3>\n<p>Before starting, make sure that you&#8217;re logged in to Thimble.</p>\n<p>First, open this link in a new browser window: <a href="https://thimbleprojects.org/mozillalearning/286539/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://thimbleprojects.org/mozillalearning/286539/</a></p>\n<p>Once there you&#8217;ll see the green remix button in the top right corner. Click this button to start your own burger remix:</p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-6688" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1-1024x542.jpg" alt="thimble the best burger project view page" width="625" height="331" srcset="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1-1024x542.jpg 1024w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1-300x159.jpg 300w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1-768x407.jpg 768w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1-189x100.jpg 189w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1-624x330.jpg 624w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1-100x53.jpg 100w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-1-750x397.jpg 750w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a></p>\n<p>Now you&#8217;ll have your own version of this project to remix. The main HTML layout structure is familiar, but notice that there are several <strong>&lt;div&gt;</strong> elements:</p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-6689" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2-1024x518.jpg" alt="thimble editor divs highlighted" width="625" height="316" srcset="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2-1024x518.jpg 1024w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2-300x152.jpg 300w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2-768x388.jpg 768w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2-198x100.jpg 198w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2-624x316.jpg 624w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2-100x51.jpg 100w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-2-750x379.jpg 750w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a></p>\n<p>The <strong>&lt;div&gt;</strong> element is essentially a container that <em>divides</em> the page into sections. In this example, each burger ingredient has its own <strong>&lt;div&gt;</strong> and <strong>class</strong>. Think of each ingredient as being a container that is then styled in the <em>ingredients.css</em> stylesheet.</p>\n<p>The classname is the <strong>selector</strong> used when identifying the element in the stylesheet. Let&#8217;s take a look at an example, the onion. The onion is given the class &#8220;onion&#8221; in the HTML, as seen above. Let&#8217;s switch to the stylesheet and locate it:</p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-6690" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3-1024x519.jpg" alt="thimble editor stylesheet onion class highlighted" width="625" height="317" srcset="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3-1024x519.jpg 1024w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3-300x152.jpg 300w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3-768x390.jpg 768w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3-197x100.jpg 197w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3-624x317.jpg 624w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3-100x51.jpg 100w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/mf-web-dev-burger-3-750x380.jpg 750w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a></p>\n<p>Remember, classes are selected by using a period followed by their name. In this case it would be <strong>.onion</strong>. Once you&#8217;ve selected that class, you&#8217;re then able to style it! Go ahead and remix the onion by changing the <em>properties</em> of the class.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonus Challenge</strong>: You may have noticed that the classes, such as the cheese, repeat! Classes are able to be repeated on a page, ids can&#8217;t. See what happens if you change one cheese and then figure out a solution to this issue.</p>\n'}},pathContext:{}}}});
